Chromium's Extension::GenerateIdForPath algorithm uses SHA-256 (not SHA-1) and always hashes the UTF-8 representation of the absolute path, even on Windows. Using SHA-1 and UTF-16LE will result in an incorrect extension ID prediction, causing the pinning logic to fail on the first launch.

```typescript
function computeExtensionIdFromPath(extensionPath: string): string {
  const absPath = path.resolve(extensionPath)
  const bytes = Buffer.from(absPath, 'utf8')
  const hex = crypto.createHash('sha256').update(bytes).digest('hex').slice(0, 32)
  const aCode = 'a'.charCodeAt(0)
  let id = ''
  for (const c of hex) {
    id += String.fromCharCode(aCode + Number.parseInt(c, 16))
  }
  return id
}
```

