The prediction logic for the extension ID currently uses SHA-1 and platform-specific encoding (UTF-16LE on Windows). However, Chromium's `Extension::GenerateIdForPath` algorithm uses SHA-256 and consistently hashes the UTF-8 representation of the absolute path, even on Windows. Using SHA-1 will lead to incorrect predictions, causing the fallback logic to trigger on every launch.

```typescript
function computeExtensionIdFromPath(extensionPath: string): string {
  const absPath = path.resolve(extensionPath)
  const bytes = Buffer.from(absPath, 'utf8')
  const hex = crypto.createHash('sha256').update(bytes).digest('hex').slice(0, 32)
  const aCode = 'a'.charCodeAt(0)
  let id = ''
  for (const c of hex) {
    id += String.fromCharCode(aCode + Number.parseInt(c, 16))
  }
  return id
}
```

