![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)

The `run` function manually joins the command and arguments into a single string when `shell: true` is used. This is fragile because it does not account for arguments that might contain spaces (e.g., if `worktreeDir` or a task hint contains a space). 

Node's `spawnSync` correctly handles an array of arguments even when `shell: true` is enabled. It will perform the necessary escaping and joining for the underlying shell (e.g., `cmd.exe` on Windows). Using the array form is safer and more robust than manual string concatenation. Additionally, the `DEP0190` warning mentioned in the comments specifically applies to `execFile` and certain `spawn` patterns where the command string is ambiguous; passing an explicit arguments array with `shell: true` is the recommended and safe way to execute commands like `.cmd` files on Windows.

```javascript
function run(cmd, args, opts = {}) {
  const r = spawnSync(cmd, args, { stdio: 'inherit', ...opts })
  if (r.status !== 0) {
    die(`command failed: ${cmd} ${args.join(' ')}`)
  }
}
```
